			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>Blade grinders destroy the beans more than grinding them &#8211; they produce an uneven grind, which means uneven extraction, and they get hot quickly, which can actually restart the roasting process and slightly burn the beans. The finer the grind, the more noticeable it is.</p>
<p>I used a very inexpensive Capresso burr grinder for a few years, but the model has been discontinued. The least expensive one I could find was this <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&#038;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FCapresso-557-01-Burr-Grinder-Black%2Fdp%2FB000O3JT46&#038;tag=meadowpartyco-20&#038;linkCode=ur2&#038;camp=1789&#038;creative=9325" rel="nofollow">basic burr grinder</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=meadowpartyco-20&amp;l=ur2&amp;o=1" width="1" height="1" border="0" alt="" style="border:none !important; margin:0px !important;" />, which seems to get mostly positive reviews, and should be more than adequate for drip or French-pressed coffee.</p>
<p>If you&#8217;re making espresso, or Turkish coffee, or some other coffee that requires a fine and precise grind, I wouldn&#8217;t use anything cheaper than the <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&#038;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FCapresso-Infinity-Burr-Grinder-Black%2Fdp%2FB0000AR7SY%2F&#038;tag=meadowpartyco-20&#038;linkCode=ur2&#038;camp=1789&#038;creative=9325" rel="nofollow">Capresso Infinity Burr Grinder</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.com/e/ir?t=meadowpartyco-20&amp;l=ur2&amp;o=1" width="1" height="1" border="0" alt="" style="border:none !important; margin:0px !important;" />, which I&#8217;ve had for about four years and have been happy with. You can get really nuts with grinders of $300-500, but obviously those are for obsessives.</p>
			</div>
			
		</li>

	
	
