		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1f708870bc614a1982c9f10ab9899ba1?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			keith 
			 on
			May 15th, 2008 9:46 am             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>Jonathan: I&#8217;ve never seen a recipe that called for brining beef, and haven&#8217;t done it myself. My guess is that even lean cuts still have enough fat in them to stay moist through cooking.</p>
<p>Brad: You can filter the oil through cheesecloth and reuse it a few times, unless it smokes during cooking, or unless it starts to smell of the food you cooked in it. When it&#8217;s time to toss it, you can pour it on the ground &#8211; it&#8217;s biodegradable &#8211; or you might find a company in your area willing to take it for resale as fuel.</p>
<p>Jason: I cook with wine all the time &#8211; never cooking wine, which is spiked with salt. I keep a bottle of vermouth in the house at all times for recipes that call for white wine, like risotto.</p>
<p>Bogart: Brad&#8217;s right about the Good Eats &#8220;What&#8217;s Up Duck?&#8221; episode &#8211; although if it&#8217;s on Youtube, that&#8217;s a copyright violation, and the uploader should be arrested and shot &#8211; which has one pretty solid technique for cooking duck. The two keys are to render out the subcutaneous fat, and to be careful not to cook the breast meat past medium, since even brined it&#8217;ll dry out.</p>
			</div>
			
		</li>

	
	
