		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1f708870bc614a1982c9f10ab9899ba1?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			keith 
			 on
			June 14th, 2008 10:00 am             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>Carol:</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve become a devotee of the &#8220;sear-roast&#8221; method for cooking thick cuts of meat, fish, or poultry indoors. It works best if you use an oven-safe skillet or saute pan. Sear it for roughly two minutes per side on the stovetop over medium-high heat to get a nice brown crust, then transfer it to the oven for 5-10 minutes at 350-375 F to cook it through. If this still overcooks the skin, reduce the searing time for the skin side to one minute and let it finish in the oven, since the pan will still be stovetop-hot even after you&#8217;ve taken it off the burner. When the meat/fish is done, drain the fat, deglaze the pan, add some minced shallots and fresh herbs and mount with butter for a quick pan sauce. And please let me know if this works for you.</p>
			</div>
			
		</li>

	
	
