		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/23713bbd37c6adda55e15226e628c523?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			Tyler 
			 on
			June 17th, 2008 5:13 pm             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>A good strong blade grinder is fine for making  coffee by drip or french press (which are the only two good methods for making hot coffee). You just might have to run it a little longer. I use one every day and my coffee is as good as Stumptown&#8217;s (or any other legendary coffee Portland coffee house). By far the most important things about making coffee are, in order:<br />
1) quality of bean (including the roast)<br />
2) freshness of bean (no freezer, grind right before making, no more than 2 weeks from roast)<br />
3) method of preparation (drip or french press depending on your taste)<br />
4) ratio of water to bean (depends on how strong you like it)</p>
<p>Everything else is of vanishingly small importance in comparison.</p>
<p>Really cheap-ass grinders: bad, sure. But a nice blade grinder is fine, I think.</p>
			</div>
			
		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1f708870bc614a1982c9f10ab9899ba1?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			keith 
			 on
			June 17th, 2008 5:18 pm             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>Tyler: I&#8217;d put freshness of bean at the top, especially for espresso, but for drip/FP as well. It makes me laugh to see Starbucks bragging about the roast dates on beans that are ten to fourteen days old. I usually won&#8217;t buy more coffee than I can consume in four or five days, and I keep it in sealed mason jars, opening them a crack if the lids start to get a little tight from CO2 release.</p>
<p>The problem with running a blade grinder a little longer is that they get hot, and can roast your coffee beans a little more than you&#8217;d like. Have you ever noticed a slight roasting or even burning smell with a blade grinder? That convinced me to upgrade to a burr.</p>
			</div>
			
		</li>

	
	
		<li>
		    <div class="commenttitle">
		    <img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/23713bbd37c6adda55e15226e628c523?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />	
			Tyler 
			 on
			June 17th, 2008 6:12 pm             </div>
            
			<div class="commenttext">
			<p>yep, mason jars are the way to go. as for freshness I have yet to detect any dropoff between a week and ten days but that might be due to good storage, or lack of detail in my perception.</p>
<p>I put quality of bean and roast first because it is the basis of flavor. You have to buy the kind of coffee you like ;o). I don&#8217;t like the super delicate light roast/single origin coffees that are the rage these days among coffee snobs, no matter how perfectly they are roasted or how fresh they are. They&#8217;re great for other people but not for me. It&#8217;s like a really superb Hefeweizen beer: I still think it sucks because that&#8217;s my taste.</p>
<p>So you just need to start with the bean, and roast, that suits your personal tastes.</p>
<p>I have never noticed that with the grinder. I am almost always doing small amounts relative to the size of the grinder, though. It&#8217;s a good point and I&#8217;ll pay attention to that.</p>
			</div>
			
		</li>

	
	
